[
  {
    "slug": "i-will-teach-you-to-be-rich",
    "title": "I Will Teach You to Be Rich",
    "subtitle": "No Guilt. No Excuses. No B.S. Just a 6-Week Program That Works.",
    "author": "Ramit Sethi",
    "asin": "1523505745",
    "isbn13": "9781523505746",
    "year": 2019,
    "pages": 352,
    "goodreads_rating": 4.05,
    "cover_url": "https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/6305971-L.jpg",
    "youtube_id": null,
    "takeaway": "Stop obsessing over lattes and focus on the big wins. Sethi's philosophy: getting rich isn't complicated—automate the basics (banking, investing, insurance) and then spend guilt-free on what matters to you. It's a practical, actionable playbook disguised as life advice, designed specifically for millennials and young professionals.",
    "key_lessons": "Focus on the 5 big money wins: optimize your bank account, negotiate your salary, automate your investments, spend intelligently on things you love\nAutomation is everything—set up automatic transfers and investments so you don't have to think about it\nYour investment strategy doesn't need to be complex: index funds are powerful and low-cost\nNegotiate your salary—most people leave thousands on the table by not asking\nDon't track every penny or cut out lattes—focus your willpower on high-impact decisions\nBuild wealth on your own terms—rich is different for different people, so design a life you want",
    "who_its_for": "Twenty-somethings, new graduates, and young professionals who feel overwhelmed by personal finance. This is the opposite of a guilt trip—it's practical without being preachy.",
    "buy_warning": null
  },
  {
    "slug": "psychology-of-money",
    "title": "The Psychology of Money",
    "subtitle": "Timeless lessons on wealth, greed, and happiness",
    "author": "Morgan Housel",
    "asin": "0857197681",
    "isbn13": "9780857197689",
    "year": 2020,
    "pages": 256,
    "goodreads_rating": 4.3,
    "cover_url": "https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/10389354-L.jpg",
    "youtube_id": null,
    "takeaway": "Money decisions aren't about math—they're about behavior. Housel argues that success with money has little to do with how smart you are and everything to do with how you behave. The book shows why two people with identical incomes can end up in completely different financial situations based on their habits, psychology, and emotional relationship with money.",
    "key_lessons": "Wealth is what you don't see—it's income minus lifestyle\nNo one is crazy—people have different goals and life experiences that shape their financial choices\nTailing risk matters more than average returns—one catastrophic mistake can wipe out decades of gains\nYou don't need to be the smartest investor; you just need to stay in the game long enough to benefit from compounding\nHumility and flexibility are more valuable than precise forecasts\nMoney is deeply personal and emotional, not purely logical",
    "who_its_for": "Anyone who feels anxious about money or comparing themselves to others. Perfect for those who want to understand *why* they make the financial decisions they do, beyond just the technical advice.",
    "buy_warning": null
  },
