  {
    "slug": "rich-dad-poor-dad",
    "title": "Rich Dad Poor Dad",
    "subtitle": "What the Rich Teach Their Kids About Money That the Poor and Middle Class Do Not!",
    "author": "Robert T. Kiyosaki",
    "asin": "1612680194",
    "isbn13": "9781612680194",
    "year": 1997,
    "pages": 336,
    "goodreads_rating": 3.7,
    "cover_url": "https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/8315603-L.jpg",
    "youtube_id": null,
    "takeaway": "The rich don't work for money—they make money work for them. Kiyosaki contrasts lessons from his 'poor dad' (his biological father) with his 'rich dad' (a family friend) to show how wealthy people think differently about assets, liabilities, and cash flow. The book's central thesis: the wealthy focus on acquiring assets that generate income, while everyone else buys liabilities they think are assets.",
    "key_lessons": "Assets put money in your pocket; liabilities take money out\nThe rich focus on their balance sheet; the poor focus on their income statement\nYou need financial literacy—understanding accounting, investing, and markets—to build wealth\nMost people work for money; the wealthy create systems and investments that work for them\nReal estate and business ownership are tools the rich use that most people never explore\nYour house is typically a liability, not an asset—the rich separate primary residence from investment property",
    "who_its_for": "Entrepreneurs, business-minded people, and anyone frustrated with the traditional \"work hard, save money\" formula. Warning: Some of Kiyosaki's claims are debated, and the real-estate strategies may not work for everyone.",
    "buy_warning": "While influential, some of Kiyosaki's financial advice and business claims have been criticized or contradicted by independent sources. Use it as inspiration to think differently about money, but verify specific strategies before implementing them."
  },
